<HEADLINE>
<P>
ON YOUR OWN: THE OUTGOING HAVE INCOME CONCERNS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HOWARD HALPERN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I have been looking back over the past year's columns to see which had the 
greatest response from readers. In May I printed a letter from Doug, 36, who 
declared, "There are not enough single women to go around for all the single 
men." He described himself in positive terms: "I was popular in high school and 
college and had no trouble getting dates. My close male friends will attest to 
the soundness of my character. At work my associates think I am witty, 
intelligent and well-read. I think my looks are above average. Even though I 
hold a responsible position as a technical writer, I admit my income is not 
that impressive." 
</P>
<P>
After he described his futile efforts to connect with women, he said: "I can 
only conclude that when single women complain that there are not enough single 
men, they mean single men who make more than $50,000 a year and look like 
models in GQ. The rest of us guys appear to be a glut on the market." 
</P>
<P>
I told Doug that I have heard this complaint from other men who say that a 
man's income is an important consideration to some women when they select a 
partner. At the same time, there are women who are more interested in a man's 
personality and character than how much money he makes. I also told Doug and 
other men with similar concerns that if they look around they will find men 
with the same occupations and income range who have close and committed 
relationships with women. I advised Doug and the others not to lose heart. 
</P>
<P>
In response to that column, a woman reader said: "I can't tell you how angry 
your response made me. Basically, you told Doug that for many women their 
interest in a man is directly related to his income! I have never asked a man 
how much money he earns. Frankly, I think that information is personal. All my 
single friends feel the same way. We are all attractive, intelligent and 
fun-loving. Most women are not such superficial opportunists. Many of us care 
about a man's deeper qualities such as his sense of humor, sensitivity and 
dependability." 
</P>
<P>
And a woman from Indiana said: "Although Doug's sense of frustration is 
understandable, please reassure him that there are many women who have learned 
to value men as people and not just as providers. Because many of us do not fit 
the ideal image of the 'perfect' woman (gorgeous, talented, etc.), we have 
developed inner qualities and values that do not view men in such a shallow and 
superficial vein. Could it be that Doug is so busy chasing after the top 5% of 
women who fit that perfect bill that he has failed to see the other women who 
can give him the very things he seeks?" 
</P>
<P>
That may be, although Doug said: "Before you warn me about the dangers of 
pursuing models or beauty queens, I would like to add that I am talking about 
average-looking women. My standards are about as broad and flexible as I can 
make them." 
</P>
<P>
You might ask: What is the relationship between a man's income and his 
desirability? Are men being cynical if they think that most women give a higher 
priority to a potential mate's income than his other qualities? Are women being 
naive if they think most women believe a man's income is of little importance? 
</P>
<P>
Here is an experiment for you to try: 
</P>
<P>
Pass out copies of the following description to a group of single women: "John 
is 35. He is quite good-looking, keeps in shape at a health club and plays 
tennis regularly. He is intelligent, has a good sense of humor and a wide range 
of interests. He is warm and sensitive, and when he cares for a woman, he can 
be very romantic and tuned-in to her feelings. Right now he is interested in a 
relationship that will lead to marriage." 
</P>
<P>
Give half the group the description in which the next sentence reads: "He 
manages the haberdashery department in a large department store and has an 
income of slightly more than $20,000 a year." Give the other half the 
description in which the next sentence reads: "He is the executive vice 
president of a chain of department stores and his income is well over six 
figures." 
</P>
<P>
The last sentence in both descriptions reads: "If you would like to meet him, 
indicate below how he may contact you." If you try this experiment, do it 
carefully. Do not give any hints that the descriptions are different. See what 
kind of results you get and let me know. 
</P>
<P>
 Questions and statements about the single life may be addressed to Howard 
Halpern in care of Special Features, 130 5th Ave., New York, N.Y. 10011. 
Unpublished letters cannot be answered individually. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
