<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jamaican Prime Minister Edward Seaga, the Reagan Administration's closest ally 
in the Caribbean, announced a parliamentary election for Feb. 9. Seaga, 58, who 
is seeking an unprecedented third consecutive four-year term, criticized his 
main rival, Socialist opposition leader Michael Manley. Seaga, at a Kingston 
rally, berated Manley's record and took credit for restoring political 
stability, economic recovery and international relations. Critics, however, say 
Seaga's economic restructuring and austerity measures have neglected social 
services and that his popularity has continued to fade. It will be Jamaica's 
first contested general election since 1980. 
</P>
